,"responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior thigh","Medial knee","Posterior calf","Lateral leg","Plantar surface of the foot"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior thigh\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct location for the L2 dermatome. This area is innervated by sensory fibers from the L2 spinal nerve root.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedial knee\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is typically associated with the L3 dermatome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral leg\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is typically associated with the L5 dermatome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior calf\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is typically associated with the S1 dermatome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlantar surface of the foot\u003C/strong\u003E - This area is typically associated with the S1 and S2 dermatomes\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the specific locations of dermatomes helps in assessing and diagnosing potential nerve root injuries or compressions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The L2 dermatome is located on the anterior thigh.","Dermatomes are areas of skin innervated by sensory fibers from a single spinal nerve root.","Understanding dermatomes is important for diagnosing nerve root injuries."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Henson B, Kadiyala B, Edens MA. Anatomy, Back, Muscles. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537074/","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press","Rockwood,